.TH JTUTIL-TRACE 1 "April 2026" "JTFRAME" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
jtutil-trace \- compare VCD output against a MAME trace
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jtutil trace
.RI [ flags ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBjtutil trace\fR
helps debug a simulation against MAME by comparing a register trace with a VCD
capture.
.PP
The default input files are:
.TP
.B debug.csv
CSV text trace generated from MAME.
It must start with a header row (for example
\fI"pc,a,x,y,frame_cnt"\fR) and each following row is one CSV sample.
.TP
.B debug.vcd
VCD file used for comparison.
.PP
Use
\fB--base-name\fR
to override those file names.
.PP
\fBdebug.csv\fR must follow a strict CSV contract:
\fIHeader\fR
line:
\fIPC,AF,BC,...\fR
followed by one line per sample.
Interrupt lines such as
\fC(interrupted at 0000F2C, IRQ 12)\fR
are accepted and converted into synthetic rows that reuse the previous register
state and expose the event text in the assembler column.
.PP
JTFRAME attempts to match MAME variables and VCD signals automatically.
If a signal is not matched, add it manually with the interactive
\fBalias\fR
command.
.PP
The comparison session is interactive, although a script can also be used.
Type
\fBhelp\fR
to list the commands.
Session commands are stored in
\fBtrace.ses\fR
and overwritten each time.
\fBsave\fR
stores the current VCD and CSV offsets in
\fB.jtutil.toml\fR so a later
\fBrestore\fR
can resume from the same position.
.PP
At the interactive prompt,
\fBo\fR
or
\fBoption\fR
sets comparison options. The supported options are:
.TP
.BI "mame-lookahead=" n
Number of MAME trace states to search while recovering a mismatch.
.TP
.BI "vcd-lookahead=" n
Number of VCD states to search while recovering a mismatch.
\fBkmax\fR
is accepted as a legacy name for the same setting.
.TP
.BI "merge-window=" n
Number of adjacent VCD states allowed to satisfy one MAME state.
.TP
.B retry
When a difference is found, try a step-trace before stopping; if there are no
differences, continue the comparison.
.TP
.BI "color=" bool
Enable ANSI color in trace-display output. The default is
.BR true .
Changed values in the
.B dt
table are highlighted in red.
.TP
.BI "table-width=" n
Limit trace display and browse tables to
.I n
columns. The default is
.BR 120 .
Overlong assembly text and table cells are truncated to keep the table within
this width.
.PP
Options entered with
\fBo\fR,
\fBoption\fR,
or the legacy
\fBkmax\fR
command are saved in
\fB.jtutil.toml\fR
in the current working directory under
\fB[trace.options]\fR.
.PP
The
\fBr\fR
or
\fBreset\fR
command restarts comparison from the initial VCD and trace position while
keeping the current option settings.
\fBsave\fR
and
\fBrestore\fR
commands persist and reload the offsets in
\fB.jtutil.toml\fR under
\fB[trace.session]\fR.
The section includes:
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBvcd_file\fR
\fIname of the VCD file\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBcsv_file\fR
\fIname of the trace CSV file\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBvcd_line\fR
\fIline number in the VCD stream\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBcsv_line\fR
\fIline number in the CSV stream\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBvcd_time\fR
\fItimestamp saved with the VCD position\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBcsv_time\fR
\fItimestamp saved with the CSV position\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBvcd_mtime_ns\fR
\fIVCD file modification timestamp (ns)\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBcsv_mtime_ns\fR
\fICSV file modification timestamp (ns)\fR
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBsaved_at\fR
\fItime when the session was saved
\fR.
Restore uses saved file modification timestamps to detect stale
or changed inputs and emits warning messages when differences are found.
.PP
Recovery messages such as exact-match and merged recovery reports are only
printed when verbose output is enabled.
.PP
The
.B dt
or
.B display-trace
command prints a table around the current MAME trace line. It displays up to
two previous lines, the current line, and up to two following lines. The
assembler text comes from CSV input rows (interrupt rows use the event text), and values that change
from the previous displayed column are highlighted when
.B color
is enabled.
The table width is limited by
.BR table-width ,
which truncates overlong assembly text and cells.
.PP
The
.B b
or
.B browse
command enters an interactive trace-table browser. It starts with the current
trace line centered like
.B dt .
Left and right move the displayed window by one trace line, Page Up and Page
Down move by five lines, Home returns to the initial centered window, and
Escape or Enter exits browse mode. Browsing does not change the active trace
comparison position.
Browse tables use the same
.B table-width
limit as
.B dt .
.PP
Comparison is paused while these signals are high:
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBalu_busy\fR:
the ALU is solving a long operation
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBstr_busy\fR:
a long string operation is in progress
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBstack_busy\fR:
stack-related long operations are in progress
.PP
If the VCD exposes
\fBtrace_seq\fR
or
\fBtrace_valid\fR,
\fBjtutil trace\fR
uses them as trace sample markers instead of advancing on any matched register
signal change.
This is useful for pipelined CPUs where several
\fBtrace_*\fR
register signals are updated in the same simulation timestamp.
.TP
.B trace_seq
Monotonic sample counter. When present, each value change marks a new coherent
CPU trace snapshot ready for comparison.
.TP
.B trace_valid
Sample-valid pulse. It is used as a fallback sample marker when
\fBtrace_seq\fR
is not present.
.PP
When neither signal is present, comparison falls back to the older behavior of
advancing to the next change in any aliased VCD signal.
.SH FLAGS
.TP
.BI "\-b, \-\-base-name " name
Use
\fB<name>.csv\fR
and
\fB<name>.vcd\fR
instead of
\fBdebug.csv\fR
and
\fBdebug.vcd\fR.
The default base name is
\fBdebug\fR.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show the short command help.
.TP
.BI "\-m, \-\-make " cpu
Create a MAME trace script for the given CPU. The generated script writes CSV
rows to \fBdebug.vcd\fR via:
\fBtrace debug.csv,CPU,noloop,{tracelog "%X,...,",...}\fR
followed by a header
\fBtracelog "PC,...,frame_cnt\\n"\fR
command.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-verbose
Enable verbose output.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR jtutil (1),
.BR jtutil-vcd (1)
